The next ten letters (the next "[[wikt:decade#English|decade]]") are the same again, but with dots at both 3 and 6 (green dots). Here ''w'' was left out as not being part of the basic French alphabet; the order is ''u v x y z ç é à è ù'' {{Braille cell|type=text|⠥|⠧|⠭|⠽|⠵|⠯|⠿|⠷|⠮|⠾}}.<ref>The values of the letters after ''z'' differ from language to language; these are Braille's assignments for French.</ref> The next ten, ending in ''w'', are the same again, except that for this series position 6 (purple dot) is used without position 3. These are ''â ê î ô û ë ï ü ö w'' {{Braille cell|type=text|⠡|⠣|⠩|⠹|⠱|⠫|⠻|⠳|⠪|⠺}}.<ref>''W'' had been tacked onto the 39 letters of the French alphabet to accommodate English.</ref> The ''a–j'' series lowered in dot space become punctuation; in English Braille these are: comma, semicolon, colon, period, (not used), exclamation point, parentheses, question mark/open quotation, (not used), close quotation: {{Braille cell|type=text|⠂|⠆|⠒|⠲|⠢|⠖|⠶|⠦|⠔|⠴}}. ''A'' and ''c'', which only use the top row, were lowered two spaces for the apostrophe and hyphen: {{Braille cell|type=text|⠄|⠤}}. (Along with the space, these are the zero characters of the first through third decade, at left in the table below.) In addition, patterns based on the first decade shifted to the right were assigned to non-French letters (''ì ä ò'' {{Braille cell|type=text|⠌|⠜|⠬}}) or serve non-letter functions: {{Braille cell|type=text|⠈}} (superscript; in English the accent mark), {{Braille cell|type=text|⠘}} (currency prefix), {{Braille cell|type=text|⠨}} (capital, in English the decimal point), {{Braille cell|type=text|⠼}} (number sign), {{Braille cell|type=text|⠸}} (emphasis mark), {{Braille cell|type=text|⠐}} (symbol prefix).

